{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584897"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:59:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:59:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14831"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14831"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.42,0.18,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114872"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7522"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14831"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96878"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7674"},{"type":"tags","id":"7879"},{"type":"tags","id":"8091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9838"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18563"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114872"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet aggregation is a crucial step in primary haemostasis that requires specific molecular interactions between platelets and plasma proteins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the molecule that enables glycoprotein IIb-IIIa to bind to fibrinogen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thromboxane A2","Adenosine diphosphate","Thrombin","Adenosine triphosphate","Protein C"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenosine diphosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is released from activated platelets and plays a crucial role in platelet aggregation. It binds to specific receptors on platelets, inducing a conformational change in the glycoprotein IIb-IIIa receptor. This change enables glycoprotein IIb-IIIa to bind fibrinogen, which forms bridges between adjacent platelets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThromboxane A2\u003C/strong\u003E promotes platelet activation but does not directly enable glycoprotein IIb-IIIa binding to fibrinogen. \u003Cstrong\u003EThrombin\u003C/strong\u003E is a potent platelet activator but does not directly mediate glycoprotein IIb-IIIa-fibrinogen binding. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdenosine triphosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is an energy molecule that does not participate directly in platelet aggregation. \u003Cstrong\u003EProtein C\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticoagulant protein that does not play a role in platelet aggregation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe binding of fibrinogen to activated glycoprotein IIb-IIIa receptors on adjacent platelets creates a platelet aggregate that forms the primary haemostatic plug.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Adenosine diphosphate is crucial for platelet activation and aggregation by enabling glycoprotein IIb-IIIa to bind to fibrinogen","Glycoprotein IIb-IIIa is a receptor on platelets that undergoes conformational change upon adenosine diphosphate binding to enable fibrinogen binding","Platelet aggregation requires both activated glycoprotein IIb-IIIa receptors and fibrinogen to form platelet-platelet bridges"],"references":["Khan M, Bordes SJ, Murray IV, et al. Physiology, Pulmonary Vasoconstriction. [Updated 2023 Apr 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499962/","Miller MA, Zachary JF. Mechanisms and Morphology of Cellular Injury, Adaptation, and Death. Pathologic Basis of Veterinary Disease. 2017:2\u201343.e19. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-323-35775-3.00001-1. Epub 2017 Feb 17. PMCID: PMC7171462","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96878"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14831"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96878"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T12:06:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T12:06:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7522"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114872"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"